Quincy Jones–polished pop best satisfies the specific combination of forward, rhythm‑locked multi‑tracked vocals with tasteful slapback, hooky bass and locked low end, punchy transient drums, concise 3–4‑minute radio singles, and restrained mastering that preserves dynamics and stems for remixing. The Elton AOR remaster, while sonically warm and well‑mastered, emphasizes piano‑forward intimacy and tucked elements that conflict with my preference for rhythm‑integrated, remix‑friendly, vocal‑forward pop — so I reject it in favor of the Quincy Jones selection.

